  "prompt": "Can Home Depot copy a car key with a chip if I provide them a blank key with a chip?",
  "response": "Home Depot offers key duplication services, but their ability to duplicate car keys with transponder chips can vary. Some Home Depot locations have the equipment to clone certain types of transponder keys, but it\u2019s not guaranteed they can handle all makes and models. Cloning a transponder key involves copying the chip's code from the existing key to the new one, which requires specialized equipment.\n\nIf you provide a blank key with a chip, there are a few factors to consider:\n\n1. **Compatibility**: The blank key must be compatible with your vehicle\u2019s system.\n2. **Capabilities**: Ensure that the Home Depot location you visit is equipped to program or clone transponder keys for your specific car make and model.\n3. **Restrictions**: Certain car manufacturers have restrictions that may prevent third-party duplication.\n\nIt\u2019s a good idea to call ahead and confirm with your local Home Depot whether they can duplicate your specific car key with a chip. Alternatively, you might consider going to an automotive locksmith or contacting your car dealership, as they typically have more comprehensive services for programming and duplicating car keys with transponder chips.",
